actions.comment:
Thanks for the thorough report and reproduction project.

Here's a workaround you can use while we investigate: serialize SVG text generation with a semaphore to prevent concurrent DirectWrite access:

```csharp
private static readonly SemaphoreSlim _svgLock = new(1, 1);

await _svgLock.WaitAsync();
try {
    using var canvas = SKSvgCanvas.Create(bounds, svgStream);
    if (canvas == null) return;
    // ... draw text ...
} finally {
    _svgLock.Release();
}
```

This eliminates the race condition at the cost of serializing SVG generation.

The issue appears to be a thread-safety problem in Skia's SVG text rendering path on Windows. When `onDrawGlyphRunList` converts glyph IDs back to Unicode characters via DirectWrite's `GetGlyphIndices`, concurrent calls can produce empty results — which explains the blank `x`/`y` attributes and missing text content. Linux uses FreeType instead of DirectWrite, which is why it's unaffected.

We'll investigate whether the fix should be a mutex in the DirectWrite code path or exposing Skia's existing `kConvertTextToPaths` flag (which bypasses glyph-to-unicode conversion entirely by emitting text as `<path>` elements).
